  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Expositor's Greek Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 1:62",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐνένευον",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (here only in N. T.): they made signs, which seems to imply that Zechariah is supposed to be deaf as well as dumb. Various suggestions have been made to evade this conclusion; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "e.g.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", that men are very apt to treat a dumb person as if he were also deaf (Bengel, De Wette, Godet); that they communicated by signs instead of by speech to spare the feelings of Elizabeth, whose judgment was being appealed from (Meyer); that a sign was all that was needed, Zechariah having heard all that was said (Bleek, J. Weiss, Hahn).—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τὸ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " before the clause following—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τί ἂν θέλοι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", viewed as a substantive, is very appropriate in a case where the question was not spoken but signalled.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἂν θέλοι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": the optative with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἂν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", implies diverse possibilities; found in Lk.’s writings only in N. T.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
